  "title": "Coin Toss Game",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "question_text": "<div class=\"paragraph\">Two friends are playing a game where you toss a fair two-sided coin. When it is your turn, you flip the coin once and record your result. Then, to keep playing you flip the coin until you no longer match your initial flip. </div><div class=\"paragraph\">Player <span class=\"tex2jax_process\">$A$</span> flips \"tails\" <span class=\"tex2jax_process\">$10$</span> straight times. Player <span class=\"tex2jax_process\">$B$</span> gets upset and thinks the coin is rigged. Player <span class=\"tex2jax_process\">$A$</span> states that since it's a random chance device, the side is not pre-determined. </div><div class=\"paragraph\">Is Player <span class=\"tex2jax_process\">$A$</span> correct?</div>",
  "image_files": [],
  "choices": [
    {
      "letter": "A",
      "text": "Yes - But the coin will most likely flip\n10\n\"heads\" on the next ten flips."
    },
    {
      "letter": "B",
      "text": "Yes - although improbable, since it's a random chance device, a pattern does not imply the data is not random."
    },
    {
      "letter": "C",
      "text": "No -\n10\n\"Tails\" in a row is impossible and the coin is rigged."
    },
    {
      "letter": "D",
      "text": "No - Since there's only two outcomes, you would be guaranteed\n5\n\"heads\" and\n5\n\"tails\" on the\n10\nflips."
    },
    {
      "letter": "E",
      "text": "No - Because \"tails\" never fails, therefore since he went first the probability of \"tails\" is greater."
    }
  ],
  "correct_answer": "<strong>Choice 'B'</strong> is the correct answer",
  "solution": "A coin is a great example of a <strong>chance device</strong> as it has two equal outcomes with the same <strong>probability</strong>. Flipping a coin will result in either a \"heads\" outcome or a \"tails\" outcome. \n\nWhen we examine the data from a chance device, it is important to note that fact that simply because there is a pattern in the data, this does not imply that the data is not random. On each flip, the coin still have an equally likely chance to land on \"heads\" or \"tails\", therefore it is theoretically possible to have <span class=\"tex2jax_process\"><span class=\"MathJax_Preview\" style=\"color: inherit;\"></span><span id=\"MathJax-Element-7932-Frame\" class=\"mjx-chtml MathJax_CHTML\" tabindex=\"0\" data-mathml=\"<math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;><mn>10</mn></math>\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"font-size: 114%; position: relative;\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36282\" class=\"mjx-math\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36283\" class=\"mjx-mrow\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36284\" class=\"mjx-mn\"><span class=\"mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R\" style=\"padding-top: 0.387em; padding-bottom: 0.387em;\">10</span></span></span></span><span class=\"MJX_Assistive_MathML\" role=\"presentation\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math></span></span><script type=\"math/tex\" id=\"MathJax-Element-7932\">10</script></span> \"tails\" in a row.\n\n<strong>Choice 'B'</strong> is correct. ",
  "distractor_explanations": {
    "A": "<strong>Choice 'A'</strong> is incorrect. Just because we had <span class=\"tex2jax_process\"><span class=\"MathJax_Preview\" style=\"color: inherit;\"></span><span id=\"MathJax-Element-7933-Frame\" class=\"mjx-chtml MathJax_CHTML\" tabindex=\"0\" data-mathml=\"<math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;><mn>10</mn></math>\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"font-size: 114%; position: relative;\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36285\" class=\"mjx-math\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36286\" class=\"mjx-mrow\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36287\" class=\"mjx-mn\"><span class=\"mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R\" style=\"padding-top: 0.387em; padding-bottom: 0.387em;\">10</span></span></span></span><span class=\"MJX_Assistive_MathML\" role=\"presentation\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math></span></span><script type=\"math/tex\" id=\"MathJax-Element-7933\">10</script></span> \"tails\" on the first ten flips, does not guarantee that the next <span class=\"tex2jax_process\"><span class=\"MathJax_Preview\" style=\"color: inherit;\"></span><span id=\"MathJax-Element-7934-Frame\" class=\"mjx-chtml MathJax_CHTML\" tabindex=\"0\" data-mathml=\"<math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;><mn>10</mn></math>\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"font-size: 114%; position: relative;\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36288\" class=\"mjx-math\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36289\" class=\"mjx-mrow\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36290\" class=\"mjx-mn\"><span class=\"mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R\" style=\"padding-top: 0.387em; padding-bottom: 0.387em;\">10</span></span></span></span><span class=\"MJX_Assistive_MathML\" role=\"presentation\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math></span></span><script type=\"math/tex\" id=\"MathJax-Element-7934\">10</script></span> will be heads. In the long run, we should see an approximately <span class=\"tex2jax_process\"><span class=\"MathJax_Preview\" style=\"color: inherit;\"></span><span id=\"MathJax-Element-7935-Frame\" class=\"mjx-chtml MathJax_CHTML\" tabindex=\"0\" data-mathml=\"<math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;><mn>50</mn><mo>&amp;#x2212;</mo><mn>50</mn></math>\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"font-size: 114%; position: relative;\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36291\" class=\"mjx-math\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36292\" class=\"mjx-mrow\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36293\" class=\"mjx-mn\"><span class=\"mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R\" style=\"padding-top: 0.387em; padding-bottom: 0.387em;\">50</span></span><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36294\" class=\"mjx-mo MJXc-space2\"><span class=\"mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R\" style=\"padding-top: 0.277em; padding-bottom: 0.441em;\">−</span></span><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36295\" class=\"mjx-mn MJXc-space2\"><span class=\"mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R\" style=\"padding-top: 0.387em; padding-bottom: 0.387em;\">50</span></span></span></span><span class=\"MJX_Assistive_MathML\" role=\"presentation\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn><mo>−</mo><mn>50</mn></math></span></span><script type=\"math/tex\" id=\"MathJax-Element-7935\">50-50</script></span> split between heads and tails, but that is after many attempts. ",
    "C": "<strong>Choice 'C'</strong> is incorrect. Although it may have a small probability of occurring, there is a probability of getting <span class=\"tex2jax_process\"><span class=\"MathJax_Preview\" style=\"color: inherit;\"></span><span id=\"MathJax-Element-7936-Frame\" class=\"mjx-chtml MathJax_CHTML\" tabindex=\"0\" data-mathml=\"<math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;><mn>10</mn></math>\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"font-size: 114%; position: relative;\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36296\" class=\"mjx-math\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36297\" class=\"mjx-mrow\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36298\" class=\"mjx-mn\"><span class=\"mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R\" style=\"padding-top: 0.387em; padding-bottom: 0.387em;\">10</span></span></span></span><span class=\"MJX_Assistive_MathML\" role=\"presentation\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn></math></span></span><script type=\"math/tex\" id=\"MathJax-Element-7936\">10</script></span> tails in a row, so it is not impossible. ",
    "D": "<strong>Choice 'D'</strong> is incorrect. As mentioned above, we are not guaranteed a <span class=\"tex2jax_process\"><span class=\"MathJax_Preview\" style=\"color: inherit;\"></span><span id=\"MathJax-Element-7937-Frame\" class=\"mjx-chtml MathJax_CHTML\" tabindex=\"0\" data-mathml=\"<math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;><mn>50</mn><mo>&amp;#x2212;</mo><mn>50</mn></math>\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"font-size: 114%; position: relative;\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36299\" class=\"mjx-math\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36300\" class=\"mjx-mrow\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36301\" class=\"mjx-mn\"><span class=\"mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R\" style=\"padding-top: 0.387em; padding-bottom: 0.387em;\">50</span></span><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36302\" class=\"mjx-mo MJXc-space2\"><span class=\"mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R\" style=\"padding-top: 0.277em; padding-bottom: 0.441em;\">−</span></span><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36303\" class=\"mjx-mn MJXc-space2\"><span class=\"mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R\" style=\"padding-top: 0.387em; padding-bottom: 0.387em;\">50</span></span></span></span><span class=\"MJX_Assistive_MathML\" role=\"presentation\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn><mo>−</mo><mn>50</mn></math></span></span><script type=\"math/tex\" id=\"MathJax-Element-7937\">50-50</script></span> split for the outcomes. But, it in long run, we should expect an approximate <span class=\"tex2jax_process\"><span class=\"MathJax_Preview\" style=\"color: inherit;\"></span><span id=\"MathJax-Element-7938-Frame\" class=\"mjx-chtml MathJax_CHTML\" tabindex=\"0\" data-mathml=\"<math xmlns=&quot;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&quot;><mn>50</mn><mo>&amp;#x2212;</mo><mn>50</mn></math>\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"font-size: 114%; position: relative;\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36304\" class=\"mjx-math\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36305\" class=\"mjx-mrow\"><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36306\" class=\"mjx-mn\"><span class=\"mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R\" style=\"padding-top: 0.387em; padding-bottom: 0.387em;\">50</span></span><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36307\" class=\"mjx-mo MJXc-space2\"><span class=\"mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R\" style=\"padding-top: 0.277em; padding-bottom: 0.441em;\">−</span></span><span id=\"MJXc-Node-36308\" class=\"mjx-mn MJXc-space2\"><span class=\"mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R\" style=\"padding-top: 0.387em; padding-bottom: 0.387em;\">50</span></span></span></span><span class=\"MJX_Assistive_MathML\" role=\"presentation\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn><mo>−</mo><mn>50</mn></math></span></span><script type=\"math/tex\" id=\"MathJax-Element-7938\">50-50</script></span> split after many attempts. ",
